Final Project- Milestone 1¶

In the first stage, we choose 2 datasets to start the project. Both datasets are downloaded from www.Kaggle.com. They are relatively clear to analysize and visualize. Since we both interested in video game, we choose our primary Video Game Sales data and Google Play Store Apps as the backup plan.

We use Video Game Sales as primary dataset since it is our common interest. This dataset contains detailed sales data in different place. The second dataset we interested in is Google Play Store Apps. This dataset provides information of 9660 unique apps on Android platform. Some of them are very polular and high-rated. A complimentary dataset would be Apple iOS app store statistics, we can also compare the performance of the same app on different platforms.

dataset 1: Video game sales¶

we get this dataset from https://www.kaggle.com/gregorut/videogamesales

The video game sales dataset contains 16,598 games with sales greater than 100,000 copies, generated by a scrape of vgchartz.com . It has 11 attributes including:

Columns of video game sales:¶

  • Rank-ranking of overall sales
  • Name-the video game name
  • Platform-platform of the games release(i.e. Wii, Nes, GB, PC, PS4, etc. 31 values)
  • Year-year of the games release
  • Genre-genre of the game(i.e. action, sports, etc. 12 values)
  • Publisher-publisher of the game(i.e. electronic arts, Activision, Nintendo, etc. 579 values)
  • NA_sales-total sales in North America(in million)
  • EU_sales-total sales in Europe(in million)
  • JP_sales-total sales in Japan(in million)
  • Other_sales-total sales in the rest of the world(in million)
  • Global_sales-total worldwide sales

Problems and interest points:¶

  • Is the ranking associates with genre or the platform?
  • What is the trend of genre of popular video games over years? Does it have relationship with the platform? How does it distributed?
  • What is the most popular platform for video games over the years? We can analyze it with the platform publication news.
  • Does different publisher has a trend to publish a specific genre of video games?
  • Compare the sales over different areas, compute the ratio between sales and population, does it have relationship with the development of the area?
  • Does different areas has different favor of genre or platform of the video game? We can analyze it considering the culture and publisher of areas.

We can visualize the above questions with kinds of vivid plots, and tidy the data focusing on each individual question.

dataset 2: Google Play Store Apps¶

we download this data from https://www.kaggle.com/lava18/google-play-store-apps

The Play Store apps data has enormous potential to drive app-making businesses to success. Some insights can be drawn for developers to work on and capture the Android market.

There are 13 columns and 9660 rows in this dataset. Each row contains a unique App from Google Play Store

Attributes of google play store apps:¶

  • App: name of the App
  • Category: type of the App
  • Rating: application's rating on playstore
  • Reviews: number of reviews
  • Size: size of app in M, sometimes varies with device.
  • Installs: number of instrallments
  • Type: whether the app is free or paid
  • Price: price of the App in dollar, if the app is free, price equals to zero
  • Content Rating: everyone, teens, mature 17+ etc. 7 values total
  • Genres: App genres(i.e. tools, education, lifestyle etc. 120 values total)
  • Last Updated: data of latest update
  • Current Ver: latest App version
  • Android Ver: Minimum Android Version required to run the App

Problems:¶

  • Why some apps are high-rated while other not?
  • Is rating related to genres?
  • Is high rating apps always updating?
  • If we are developing a new app on Android, how to get our app high_rated?
  • Given other information, can we predict the rating of an app?

Ranking over Genre/Platform¶

In this part, we would like to investigate if the ranking is associated with genre or the platform. We only consider the top 500 rank over the table, since we think the rest may not be representative and may affect the result, we used bar plots of the mean rank vs. genre/platform to visualize them. The shorter of the bar, the higher ranking of the genre/platform.

  • From the first plot(mean ranking over genre), platform and racing games have higher ranking, while fighing and adventure games have lower ranking.
  • From the second plot(mean ranking over platform), GB and Wii have higher ranking, XOne PC and PS2 have lower ranking.

Trends of Genre or Platform over Years¶

In this part, we want to know the trend of genre/platform of popular video games over years. We calculate how many game published in the specific year of each genre and platform. Since there are so many platform, and lots of them are not well-known, we only plot the top 10 platforms which has the most video games.

  • From the first plot(overall video game over year),there are rarely video games before 1990, the video games market starts to thrive from 1990, the market arrives its peak around 2009, and start to drop off after 2010.
  • From the second plot(trends of genre over years) and third plot(overall video game counts by genre), action and sports games are accounted for a large part, sports video games first thrives around 2002, and action video games catch up around 2006.
  • From the fourth plot(overall video game counts by platform), most video games are published on only few platform, they are not evenly distributed, we can only count for the top 10 platform.
  • From the fifth plot(trends of top10 platform over years) and sixth plot(overall video game counts by top10 platform), PS took over the market over 1995-2000, PS2 GBA XB took over the market over 2000-2005, DS took the majority of th market in 2009, followed by Wii and X360. But PC exists the longest period, it becomes popular since 1985., although it doesn't take much of the market. DS and PS2 published the highest number of video games.
  • From the seventh plot(genre vs. platform heatmap), sports video games are popular in PS2, music video games are popular in DS, and action video games are popular in DS, PS2, etc.

Sales (Percentage) of Each Area in Each Genre¶

In this part, we are interested in each genre of video games sales in every area. We drawed heatmap among genre and area in absolute sale numbers and percentage sales, and the percentage is more clear than the actual amount, NA take a large amount in every genre, but JP has flavor in Role-Playing specifically, which is quite fitting in the Japanese Cosplay culture. To be more clear, we also drawed stacked bar plot of the percentage plot.

In [81]:
genre=vgsales_df.groupby("Genre").sum()
genre["NA_Sales_Per"]=genre["NA_Sales"]/genre["Global_Sales"]
genre["EU_Sales_Per"]=genre["EU_Sales"]/genre["Global_Sales"]
genre["JP_Sales_Per"]=genre["JP_Sales"]/genre["Global_Sales"]
genre["Other_Sales_Per"]=genre["Other_Sales"]/genre["Global_Sales"]
plt.figure(figsize=(8,12))
plt.subplot(211)
sns.set(font_scale=0.6)
sales=genre.loc[:,'NA_Sales':'Other_Sales']
ax1=sns.heatmap(sales, annot=True, fmt = '.1f')
bottom,top=ax1.get_ylim()
ax1.set_ylim(bottom,top)
plt.title("Sales of Each Area in Each Genre")
plt.subplot(212)
percen=genre.loc[:,'NA_Sales_Per':'Other_Sales_Per']
ax2=sns.heatmap(percen, vmax =1, vmin=0, annot=True, fmt = '.2%')
bottom,top=ax2.get_ylim()
ax2.set_ylim(bottom,top)
plt.title("Sales Percentage of Each Area in Each Genre")
plt.show()

Trends of Area Sales (Percentage) over Years¶

In this part, we ploted the sales percentage of four areas over years to see the trends. It fits the conclusion we got from above sections.

  • the video games market starts to thrive from 1995, the market arrives its peak around 2009, and start to drop off after 2010.
  • NA takes a large amount in sales market.
  • JP also takes a large amount around 1953-1955 and 2015-now. Since the sales are measured in money, we need to consider the population of each area, Japan apparently has smaller population across the four areas, but it still takes a large part of the markets, which means video games are heated in Japan across the long time.
In [83]:
years=vgsales_df.groupby("Year").sum()
years["NA_Sales_Per"]=years["NA_Sales"]/years["Global_Sales"]
years["EU_Sales_Per"]=years["EU_Sales"]/years["Global_Sales"]
years["JP_Sales_Per"]=years["JP_Sales"]/years["Global_Sales"]
years["Other_Sales_Per"]=years["Other_Sales"]/years["Global_Sales"]

Correlation of GDP of Areas¶

In this part, we found a dataset of GDP in NA, EU, JP and world. We grouped the video games dataset by years, and sum the sales for each year, we computed the correlation coefficient of sales and GDP for each area across year and made a bar plot to visualize it. All the correlation coefficients are positive and over 0.6, which makes sense to say the sales is positive correlative with GDP.

genre = vgsales_df['Genre'].unique()
labels = genre
sns.set(font_scale = 0.8)
for publisher in great_pub:
    markers = np.linspace(0,max(pub_genre[publisher]),num = 11)
    str_markers = [str(x) for x in markers]
    def radar_chart(title, stats, att_labels = labels, plot_markers = markers, plot_str_markers = str_markers):

        labels = np.array(att_labels)

        angles = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, len(labels), endpoint=False)
        stats = np.concatenate((stats,[stats[0]]))
        angles = np.concatenate((angles,[angles[0]]))

        fig= plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
        ax = fig.add_subplot(111, polar=True)
        ax.plot(angles, stats, '.-', linewidth=1)
        ax.fill(angles, stats, alpha=0.25)
        ax.set_thetagrids(angles * 180/np.pi, labels)
        plt.yticks(markers)
        ax.set_title(title)
        ax.grid(True)

        return plt.show()

    radar_chart(publisher, pub_genre[publisher])

From the above radar chart, we can see the top publisher in the industry do have a preference of making different genres of games. Nintendo's kind of a balanced-development company, which is good at puzzle, simulation and role-playing, while Activision extremely loves sports and Take-Two interactive preferred adventure.
